Desmiophyllum sp. Pl. 6, figs. 1—3.

The fragments shown in pl. 6, figs. 1—-3, are best men- tioned under the provisional name Desmiophyllum.

The specimens represent portions of linear leaves, or segments of compound ones, reaching a length of 3-4 cm, with a breadth of up to 7 mm. The specimen in fig. l is distinctly tapered towards the base, the one in fig. 2 has almost parallel edges. Both specimens have simple, parallel veins, 8-12 in number. In the specimen in fig. 2, there can be seen a much finer interstitial vein between each two of the stronger ones (fig. 3). There is some difference between the specimens. The one in fig. l has denser veins and shows no interstitial veins, though it may well possess such. The occurrence of intermediate speoimens, however, renders the identity probable.

It is impossible to state the exact nature of these fragments.
